Those in the control room are employees of a quasi-governmental entity called ERCOT, the Electrical Reliability Council of Texas. As the first hot days of Texas summer count down to the scorching temperatures of late July and August, ERCOT managers say the grid is prepared. It's ready to meet the demands of 20 million Texans; ready to deal with another peak day like that of Aug. 7, 2003, when the state's electrical usage reached a record 60,095 megawatts. Studies of the outages indicated problems in Canada cascaded into the Northeast, leaving New York and Detroit without power for days. 